It's called the Barefoot College, and its founder, Bunker Roy, explains how it works.", "event": "TEDGlobal 2011", "language": "en", "language_swap": false, "name": "Bunker Roy: Learning from a barefoot movement", "slug": "bunker_roy", "series_slug": null, "speakers": [{"id": "1000", "slug": "bunker_roy", "is_published": true, "firstname": "Bunker", "lastname": "Roy", "middleinitial": "", "title": "", "description": "Educator", "photo_url": "https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/eebdec068c3b0e7e783ae87c56193c42d70a1ce5_254x191.jpg", "whatotherssay": "Roy's idea is that India and Africa are full of people with skills, knowledge and resourcefulness who are not recognised as engineers, architects or water experts but who can bring more to communities than governments or big businesses.", "whotheyare": "Sanjit \u201cBunker\u201d Roy is the founder of Barefoot College, which helps rural communities becomes self-sufficient.", "whylisten": "

Development projects the world over run into one crucial point: For a project to live on, it needs to be organic, owned and sustained by those it serves. In 1972,  Sanjit “Bunker” Roy founded the Barefoot College, in the village of Tilonia in Rajasthan, India, with just this mission: to provide basic services and solutions in rural communities with the objective of making them self-sufficient. These “barefoot solutions” can be broadly categorized into solar energy, water, education, health care, rural handicrafts, people’s action, communication, women’s empowerment and wasteland development. The Barefoot College education program, for instance, teaches literacy and also skills, encouraging learning-by-doing. (Literacy is only part of it.)  Bunker’s organization has also successfully trained grandmothers from Africa and the Himalayan region to be solar engineers so they can bring electricity to their remote villages.

As he says, Barefoot College is "a place of learning and unlearning: where the teacher is the learner and the learner is the teacher."

Roy is the founder of Barefoot College, which helps rural communities becomes self-sufficient.", "whylisten": "

Development projects the world over run into one crucial point: For a project to live on, it needs to be organic, owned and sustained by those it serves. In 1972,  Sanjit “Bunker” Roy founded the Barefoot College, in the village of Tilonia in Rajasthan, India, with just this mission: to provide basic services and solutions in rural communities with the objective of making them self-sufficient. These “barefoot solutions” can be broadly categorized into solar energy, water, education, health care, rural handicrafts, people’s action, communication, women’s empowerment and wasteland development. The Barefoot College education program, for instance, teaches literacy and also skills, encouraging learning-by-doing. (Literacy is only part of it.)  Bunker’s organization has also successfully trained grandmothers from Africa and the Himalayan region to be solar engineers so they can bring electricity to their remote villages.

As he says, Barefoot College is "a place of learning and unlearning: where the teacher is the learner and the learner is the teacher."
